The last excep- tion, therefore, against them is, that they were but a provin- cial counoili, and of very little authority in the Church, having never been confirmed by the pope. But there is no part of this exception true. For, first, it was a council that consisted of divers provinces or regions of Asiak, which makes it greater than any provincial synod¹. Secondly, it was al- ways held to be of great veneration and authority ¹1¹, both in the Greek and in the Latin Church. And, thirdly, although the oriental councils in those days needed no confirmation from the pope, (who claimed no such jurisdiction then, as he did in after ages, over those places that were out of his own limits”,) yet that, among other councils of the east, the popes received this in the west, and acknowledged the canons of it to be a part of those ecclesiastica] rules whereby both themselves and other bishops were to be guided, we find it manifest in the letter⁰ that Pope Leo IV. sent to the bishops
